<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="76" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,934,1250]" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
<keyLead pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
1. T1 without posteromedian spot of pale setae. T2 with two subbasal spots of pale setae separated by distance at most equal to their own diameter. Dorsal propodeal face posterad with small median tubercle.— 
<collectingCountry box="[1013,1071,964,986]" name="Egypt" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1084,1198,964,986]" country="Egypt" name="Janub Sina'" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">South Sinai</collectingRegion>
)......................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Soliman" authorityName="Soliman" box="[1087,1255,992,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Macromyrme" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leleji">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1087,1169,992,1014]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">M. leleji</emphasis>
Soliman
</taxonomicName>
in El-Torkey 
<emphasis box="[1388,1437,993,1015]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,934,1250]" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
<keyLead pageId="15" pageNumber="76">- T1 with posteromedian quadrangular spot of pale setae that extends onto T2. T2 with two subbasal spots of pale setae separated by distance more than their own diameter. Dorsal propodeal face posterad with well developed median tubercle.......... 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,934,1250]" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
<keyLead pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
2. Antennal tubercle with denticle. Mesopleuron with precoxal carina. Clypeus basally with two well-developed larger lateral and one smaller medial tubercles. Propleuron anterad with complete vertical carina. Pygidial area basally granulated with rare longitudinal rugae............................ 
<taxonomicName authority="(Olivier)" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" box="[741,938,1139,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Mutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[741,848,1139,1161]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">M. sinuata</emphasis>
(Olivier)
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName authority="Rad." authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1890" box="[971,1192,1140,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Mutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="araratica">
<emphasis box="[971,1139,1140,1161]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">Mutilla araratica</emphasis>
Rad.
</taxonomicName>
, = 
<taxonomicName authority="Rad." authorityName="Radoszkowski" authorityYear="1879" box="[1221,1430,1140,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Mutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="binotata">
<emphasis box="[1221,1378,1140,1161]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">Mutilla binotata</emphasis>
Rad.
</taxonomicName>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,934,1250]" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
<keyLead pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
- Antennal tubercle without denticle. Mesopleuron without precoxal carina. Clypeus basally without developed tubercles. Propleuron anterad with vertical carina in upper half. Pygidial area basally finely rugulated without longitudinal rugae........................................................................... 
